This pull request contains `_.replaceAll` static function. Default behavior of JavaScript's `String.prototype.replace` is to replace only first occurence of a string (unless `RegExp` is used) and `_.replaceAll` replaces all occurences. 

``` JavaScript
_.replaceAll('b-c-d', '-', '.');
// => 'b.c.d'
```

It could be eventually further improved in the future to work in a chain like this:

``` JavaScript
_(['a.b.c', 'def']).replaceAll('.', '..').value(); 
// => ['a..b..c', 'def']
```

I wanted to make my own aggregator. Specifically, a groupBy that would group on array fields and allow records to appear in multiple groups.

```
var multiValuedGroupBy = _.createAggregator(function(result, value, keys) {
    _.each(keys, function(key) {
    if (_.has(result, key)) {
        result[key].push(value);
    } else {
        result[key] = [value];
    }
    });
})
```

So, `multiValuedGroupBy([{A:[1,2],B:0},{A:[1,3],B:0}], 'A')` produces:

```
{
     "1":[{"A":[1,2],"B":0},{"A":[1,3],"B":0}],
     "2":[{"A":[1,2],"B":0}],
     "3":[{"A":[1,3],"B":0}]
 }
```

I couldn't just make a `multiValuedGroupBy` mixin because I needed access to createAggregator.

