### What This Does

Gives you a new array of elements from the array/collection matching the indexes provided. 
### Why I Made This

I've had this come up a few times in applications, namely when using collections as a data-source. In my latest situation, I have a collection that is the data-source for a slick-grid. When getting the selected rows, an array of which rows (e.g., `[3,5,6,7,9]`) is returned. Since lodash has so many other convenient methods to access arrays and collections, this seemed quite sensible to be able to `_.at( collection, rows )`. 

I also think some nifty stuff could be done by combining _.range with this.

I added 3rd argument "args" that is passed to method if it is a function:

